channel.title: NASA Image of the Day
channel.description: The latest NASA "Image of the Day" image.

item.title: Northrop Grumman Cargo Mission Awaits Launch
item.description: Northrop Grumman’s 13th contracted cargo resupply mission with NASA to the International Space Station will deliver about 7,500 pounds of science and research, crew supplies and vehicle hardware to the orbital laboratory and its crew.

item.title: Victor Glover: Training for the Future
item.description: NASA astronaut Victor Glover trains on POGO--the Partial Gravity Simulator at Building 9N's Space Vehicle Mockup Training Facility at the Johnson Space Center.

item.title: Record-Setting NASA Astronaut, Crewmates Return from Space Station
item.description: NASA astronaut Christina Koch is seen outside the Soyuz MS-13 spacecraft after she, Roscosmos cosmonaut Alexander Skvortsov, and ESA astronaut Luca Parmitano, landed.

item.title: Trailblazers: The Story of a Tuskegee Airman
item.description: Retired U.S. Air Force Honorary Brigadier General Charles McGee speaks with NASA astronaut Alvin Drew during a Black History Month program

item.title: Astronaut Christina Koch's Record-Setting Mission
item.description: NASA astronaut Christina Koch is set to return to Earth on Thursday, Feb. 6, after 328 days living and working aboard the International Space Station.

item.title: Deborah Johnson: A Career in the Service of Space Exploration
item.description: Deborah Johnson has worked for NASA since 1978.

item.title: NASA Day of Remembrance
item.description: Amy Resnik touches the Space Shuttle Challenger Memorial after a wreath laying ceremony as part of NASA’s Day of Remembrance, Thursday, Jan. 30, 2020, at Arlington National Cemetery.

item.title: Luca Parmitano Works to Repair the Alpha Magnetic Spectrometer
item.description: Astronaut and station commander Luca Parmitano is tethered to the International Space Station while finalizing thermal repairs on the AMS.

item.title: Chandra Spots a Mega-Cluster of Galaxies in the Making
item.description: Astronomers using data from NASA's Chandra X-ray Observatory and other telescopes have put together a detailed map of a rare collision between four galaxy clusters.

item.title: Spitzer Observes TRAPPIST-1
item.description: Spitzer Space Telescope, one of agency’s great observatories, one of Spitzer's great discoveries was that of the TRAPPIST-1 star, an ultra-cool dwarf, which has seven Earth-size planets orbiting it.

item.title: Setting the Stage for Artemis Testing
item.description: All eyes are on south Mississippi with this month’s delivery and installation of NASA’s Space Launch System.

item.title: Martin Luther King Day of Service at NASA Headquarters
item.description: The Amidon-Bowen Elementary School choir performs at the MLK Day of Service.

item.title: Liftoff of SpaceX's In-Flight Abort Test
item.description: SpaceX's Falcon 9 rocket lifts off from Launch Complex 39A at the Kennedy Space Center at 10:30 a.m. EST on Jan. 19, 2020.

item.title: Hubble Views Galaxy From Famous Catalog
item.description: This bright, somewhat blob-like object — seen in this image taken by the NASA/ESA Hubble Space Telescope — is a galaxy named NGC 1803. It is about 200 million light-years away, in the southern constellation of Pictor (the Painter’s Easel), and it was discovered in 1834 by astronomer John Herschel.

item.title: Cuatro Cienegas Basin, Mexico
item.description: In the northern Mexican state of Cohuilla lies the Cuatro Cienegas Basin.

item.title: Astronauts Nick Hague and Anne McClain at the National Air and Space Museum
item.description: NASA astronauts Nick Hague and Anne McClain talk about their experiences onboard the International Space Station at the Smithsonian National Air and Space Museum in D.C.

item.title: NASA's Juno Spacecraft Has a Close Encounter with Jupiter
item.description: A multitude of swirling clouds in Jupiter's dynamic North North Temperate Belt is captured in this image from NASA's Juno spacecraft.

item.title: Welcoming NASA’s Newest Astronauts
item.description: NASA welcomed 11 new astronauts to its ranks Friday.

item.title: Observing Titan for Signs of Life
item.description: NASA has announced that our next destination in the solar system is the unique, richly organic world Titan.

item.title: What Happens When Planets Collide
item.description: This artist’s concept illustrates a catastrophic collision between two rocky exoplanets, turning both into dusty debris.

item.title: A waxing crescent Moon
item.description: A waxing crescent Moon is pictured as the International Space Station orbited 260 miles above the north African country of Algeria.

item.title: TESS Finds First Earth-Size Planet in the Habitable Zone
item.description: TOI 700 d is the first Earth-size habitable-zone planet discovered by TESS, NASA's Transiting Exoplanet Survey Satellite.

item.title: The Next Step in Testing Rockets to Take Humanity to the Moon
item.description: On Jan.1, 2020, ​​NASA Administrator Jim Bridenstine tweeted: "Making progress! The massive @NASA_SLS core stage is moving to Building 110 at the Michoud Assembly Facility.

item.title: Hubble Sights Galaxy’s Celestial Sequins
item.description: This smattering of celestial sequins is a spiral galaxy named NGC 4455, located in the northern constellation of Coma Berenices (Berenice’s Hair). This might sound like an odd name for a constellation — and in fact it is somewhat unusual. It’s the only modern constellation named in honor of a real person from history: Queen Berenice II of Egypt.

item.title: Glittering Lights of Earth As Seen From the Space Station
item.description: Stars glitter in the night sky above the Earth's atmospheric glow.

item.title: Galactic Pyrotechnics From 23 Million Light Years Away
item.description: NGC 4258, a galaxy about 23 million light years away, is the site of impressive, ongoing fireworks.

item.title: Exploring the Night Sky with Hubble’s Caldwell Catalog
item.description: This loose collections of stars, known as an open star cluster, is image 100 of the Caldwell catalog.

item.title: Astronaut Christina Koch Poised to Make History Again
item.description: NASA astronaut Christina Koch makes observations from the International space Station's cupola.

item.title: Morocco's Anti-Atlas Mountains
item.description: The Anti-Atlas Mountains of Morocco formed as a result of the collision of the African and Eurasian tectonic plates about 80 million years ago.

item.title: Stellar Snowflake Cluster
item.description: The newly revealed infant stars appear as pink and red specks toward the center and appear to have formed in regularly spaced intervals along linear structures.

item.title: Hubble’s Close-Up of Spiral’s Disk, Bulge
item.description: ​This image from the NASA/ESA Hubble Space Telescope shows IC 2051, a galaxy in the southern constellation of Mensa (the Table Mountain) lying about 85 million light-years away. It is a spiral galaxy, as evidenced by its characteristic whirling, pinwheeling arms, and it has a bar of stars slicing through its center.

item.title: This Week in NASA History: 3rd Hubble Servicing Mission – Dec. 19, 1999
item.description: This week in 1999, space shuttle Discovery, mission STS-103, launched from NASA’s Kennedy Space Center on the third Hubble Space Telescope servicing mission.

item.title: Galaxy Gathering Brings Warmth
item.description: As the holiday season approaches, people in the northern hemisphere will gather indoors to stay warm. In keeping with the season, astronomers have studied two groups of galaxies that are rushing together and producing their own warmth.

item.title: Hubble Views Galaxy’s Dazzling Display
item.description: ​NGC 3175 is located around 50 million light-years away in the constellation of Antlia (the Air Pump). The galaxy can be seen slicing across the frame in this Hubble image, with its mix of bright patches of glowing gas, dark lanes of dust, bright core, and whirling, pinwheeling arms coming together to paint a beautiful celestial scene.

item.title: The Canadarm2 robotic arm with the Dextre robotic hand
item.description: The Canadarm2 robotic arm with the Dextre robotic hand attached seemingly protrudes from the side of the International Space Station.

item.title: A Treat for the International Space Station's First Crew
item.description: In this image from December 2000, the Expedition One crew--the first to permanently inhabit the International Space Station--are about to eat a treat of fresh oranges.

item.title: Brilliance at Night: The Americas in Darkness
item.description: This image of North and South America at night is a composite assembled from data acquired by the Suomi NPP satellite in April and October 2012.

item.title: Earth's Changing Ice
item.description: Meltwater lakes form on the surface of Greenland’s Petermann Glacier.

item.title: Houston, Texas on the Gulf Coast
item.description: Houston, Texas is pictured from the International Space Station at an altitude of 257 miles.

item.title: Progress 73 Cargo Craft Departs the Station
item.description: To make room for the latest cargo craft on Nov. 29, Progress 73 departed the station after undocking from the Pirs docking compartment.

item.title: Hubble Spots Galaxy’s Dramatic Details
item.description: Some of the most dramatic events in the universe occur when certain stars die — and explode catastrophically in the process. When these star deaths, or supernovae, occur, their brightness can rival the light of a whole galaxy. The galaxy NGC 5468, shown in this Hubble image, has hosted a number of these supernovae the past 20 years.

item.title: Luca Parmitano Works to Upgrade a Cosmic Particle Detector
item.description: European Space Agency astronaut and current International Space Station Commander Luca Parmitano and ​crewmate Andrew Morgan (out of frame) performed the third spacewalk to repair the Alpha Magnetic Spectrometer.

item.title: Carina Nebula's 'Mystic Mountain'
item.description: Within the tempestuous Carina Nebula lies “Mystic Mountain.”

item.title: ‘Robot Hotel’ Launching to the International Space Station
item.description: Robots need a place to stay in space, too. NASA is attaching a “robot hotel” to the outside of the International Space Station with the upcoming launch of the Robotic Tool Stowage (RiTS).

item.title: Glancing Back
item.description: Just after its close flyby of Jupiter on Nov. 3, 2019, NASA's Juno spacecraft caught this striking view of Jupiter's southern hemisphere as the spacecraft sped away from the giant planet. This image captures massive cyclones near Jupiter's south pole, as well as the chaotic clouds of the folded filamentary region.

item.title: Black Hole Nurtures Baby Stars a Million Light-Years Away
item.description: Black holes are famous for ripping objects apart, including stars. But now, astronomers have uncovered a black hole that may have sparked the births of stars over a mind-boggling distance, and across multiple galaxies.

item.title: Thanksgiving 2019 Aboard the Space Station
item.description: See what the holiday means to NASA’s Christina Koch, Jessica Meir and Andrew Morgan aboard the International Space Station.

item.title: Inspiring a New Generation of Astronauts
item.description: Native American NASA Astronaut, John Herrington is pictured here with Lucasti and Caibiya Tsabetsaye in front of the NASA Artemis banner at the 2019 American Indian Science and Engineering Society’s National Conference.

item.title: Astronauts Complete 2nd Phase to Repair Alpha Magnetic Spectrometer
item.description: Astronaut Andrew Morgan is tethered to the Starboard-3 truss segment work site during the second spacewalk to repair the International Space Station's cosmic particle detector, the Alpha Magnetic Spectrometer.

item.title: Hubble Eyes an Emitting Galaxy
item.description: For this image, the NASA/ESA Hubble Space Telescope turned its powerful eye toward an emission-line galaxy called NGC 3749. It lies over 135 million light-years away and is moderately luminous.

item.title: Edward Gonzales: Advocating for Underserved Communities
item.description: Eddie Gonzales works to mentor Native American students and others in underserved communities.

item.title: Stars Are Being Born in the Depths of a Black Hole
item.description: In the Phoenix constellation, astronomers have confirmed the first example of a galaxy cluster where large numbers of stars are being born at its core.

item.title: George Gorospe: From Intern to Research Engineer
item.description: Born and raised in Albuquerque, New Mexico, George Gorospe was taught by his parents to take pride in his Native American heritage.

item.title: Astronauts Complete First Excursion to Repair Cosmic Particle Detector
item.description: Station Commander ​​Luca Parmitano of the European Space Agency conducts repairs, while attached to the Canadarm during the first spacewalk to repair the Alpha Magnetic Spectrometer.

item.title: Hubble Spots a Curious Spiral
item.description: Many galaxies we see through telescopes such as the NASA/ESA Hubble Space Telescope, the source of this beautiful image, look relatively similar: spiraling arms, a glowing center, and a mixture of bright specks of star formation and dark ripples of cosmic dust weaving throughout. This galaxy, a spiral galaxy named NGC 772, is no exception.

item.title: Apollo 12 Sees a Solar Eclipse
item.description: Fifty years ago, on Nov. 14, 1969, Apollo 12 launched at 11:22 a.m. EST from Launch Complex 39A at the Kennedy Space Center in Florida.

item.title: Powtawche Valerino: Supporting NASA’s Space Launch System Program
item.description: Powtawche Valerino is a guidance engineer who works for Aerodyne Industries at the NASA's Marshall Space Flight Center, supporting the agency’s Space Launch System program.

item.title: Mercury's Solar Transit
item.description: The planet Mercury is seen in silhouette, low center, as it transits across the face of the Sun, Monday, Nov. 11, 2019.

item.title: Building the Rover of the Future
item.description: A student from Sinte Gleska University works to build a model rover for a NASA Community College Aerospace Scholars.

item.title: This Week in NASA History: First Launch of Saturn V – Nov. 9, 1967
item.description: This week in 1967, the Apollo 4 mission launched from NASA’s Kennedy Space Center.
